        <header>
            <h1>Pharmacy Calculations Course</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">How to Convert Kilogram to Gram</p>
        </header>
        
        <div class="lesson-content">
            <div class="pharmacy-context">
                <h3>Why This Matters in Pharmacy</h3>
                <p>In the field of pharmacy, accurate calculations are crucial to ensure the correct dosage and administration of medications. One common calculation that pharmacists frequently encounter is the conversion of units of measurement. While kilograms are used for bulk quantities in manufacturing and inventory, grams and milligrams are used for compounding and individual dosing.</p>
            </div>
            
            <h2>Understanding the Relationship</h2>
            <p>Before we begin, it's important to understand the relationship between kilograms and grams. The conversion factor for converting kilograms to grams is <span class="highlight">1000</span>. This means that:</p>
            
            <div class="conversion-formula">
                1 kilogram (kg) = 1000 grams (g)
            </div>
            
            <div class="visualization">
                <div class="kg-block" id="kg-block">1 kg</div>
                <div class="conversion-arrow">→</div>
                <div class="g-container" id="g-container">
                    <!-- Gram blocks will be generated by JavaScript -->
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-number">1</div>
                <h3>Step 1: Understand the Conversion Factor</h3>
                <p>The conversion factor is the number you multiply by to convert from one unit to another. For kg to g:</p>
                <div class="conversion-formula">Conversion Factor = 1000</div>
                <p>This means every kilogram contains 1000 grams. Think of it like this: 1 kg is 1000 times larger than 1 g.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-number">2</div>
                <h3>Step 2: Set Up the Conversion Equation</h3>
                <p>To convert kilograms to grams, use this simple equation:</p>
                <div class="conversion-formula">
                    Number of kilograms × 1000 = Number of grams
                </div>
                <p>Or written mathematically:</p>
                <div class="conversion-formula">g = kg × 1000</div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Example:</h4>
                    <p>Let's say we have 2 kilograms that we want to convert to grams. We can set up the equation as:</p>
                    <div class="conversion-formula">2 kg × 1000 = ? g</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-number">3</div>
                <h3>Step 3: Perform the Calculation</h3>
                <p>Multiply the number of kilograms by 1000 to find the number of grams.</p>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Continuing our example:</h4>
                    <div class="conversion-formula">2 kg × 1000 = 2000 g</div>
                    <p>So, 2 kilograms is equal to 2000 grams.</p>
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>Simple trick:</strong> When multiplying by 1000, just add three zeros to the number, or move the decimal point three places to the right.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-number">4</div>
                <h3>Step 4: Check Your Answer</h3>
                <p>Always double-check your calculations in pharmacy work. To verify, convert the grams back to kilograms using the reverse calculation:</p>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Verifying our example:</h4>
                    <div class="conversion-formula">2000 g ÷ 1000 = 2 kg</div>
                    <p>As expected, the result is 2 kilograms, confirming our conversion was correct.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-points">
                <h3>Key Points to Remember</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>1 kg = 1000 g (always remember this conversion factor)</li>
                    <li>To convert kg to g: <strong>Multiply by 1000</strong></li>
                    <li>To convert g to kg: <strong>Divide by 1000</strong></li>
                    <li>In pharmacy, you'll often need to convert further to mg (1 g = 1000 mg)</li>
                    <li>Always double-check your work, especially with medication calculations</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="practice-area">
                <h2>Interactive Conversion Tool</h2>
